section.section:
The Board of Trustees may not:
set or increase the salary for the deputy chief investment officer at an amount greater than the maximum salary under the ES11 scale of the Maryland Executive Pay Plan;
set or increase the salary for a managing director at an amount greater than the maximum salary under the ES9 scale of the Maryland Executive Pay Plan;
provide bonuses for an employee; or
subject to the limitations under items (i) and (ii) of this paragraph, set or increase the salary for a position that provides more than a 10% increase over the lowest salary for the position in the prior fiscal year.

On or before October 1, 2012, and each October 1 thereafter, the Board of Trustees shall report to the Senate Budget and Taxation Committee, the House Appropriations Committee, and the Joint Committee on Pensions, in accordance with § 2-1246 of the State Government Article on:
the current salaries of the deputy chief investment officer and the managing directors of the Investment Division;
any salary increases the deputy chief investment officer or managing directors of the Investment Division have received in the fiscal year immediately preceding that October 1; and
the number of individuals in the Investment Division of the State Retirement Agency who were employed as professional investment staff and terminated employment with the State Retirement Agency in the fiscal year immediately preceding that October 1;
the number of years of employment an individual described in item 1 of this item had accrued with the State Retirement Agency at the time the individual terminated employment with the State Retirement Agency; and
to the extent possible, the new employer, position, and salary the individual described in item 1 of this item accepted upon terminating employment with the State Retirement Agency.

The report shall detail:
the identity of each recipient of a commission that the State Retirement Agency paid during the previous quarter;
the dollar amount of commission business that each recipient performs;
the average price-per-share each recipient charged or, if the commission was paid on a net basis, the markup or markdown that the recipient uses; and
a reasonable history of the allocation of commissions.
